list-type: square;

To make a list that lists its items with squares, you can use the `list-style-type` property and set its value to `square`.

Example:

```
ul {
  list-style-type: square;
}
```

This will display the items of an unordered list (ul) with square bullets.

To select an element with id `demo`, you can use the CSS selector `#demo`.

Example:

```
#demo {
  color: red;
}
```

This will select the element with id `demo` and apply a red color to it. The `#` symbol is used to indicate that the selector is looking for an element with a specific id.

To select elements with class name `test`, you can use the CSS selector `.test`.

Example:

```
.test {
  font-size: 16px;
}
```

This will select all elements with class name `test` and apply a font size of 16 pixels to them. The `.` symbol is used to indicate that the selector is looking for elements with a specific class name.

To group selectors, you can separate each selector with a comma. 

Example:

```
h1, h2, h3 {
  color: blue;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}
```

This code will select all `h1`, `h2`, and `h3` elements and apply the same styles to them. 

Alternatively, CSS rules can also be written separately, following the same style declaration:

```
h1 {
  color: blue;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

h2 {
  color: blue;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}

h3 {
  color: blue;
  font-family: Arial, sans-serif;
}
``` 

However, grouping selectors is a more concise way of writing the same set of rules.
